ce:section.ce:para:
The detailed synthetic route of P-CDs/TiO2@CS is presented in Scheme 1. First, P-CDs were synthesized from peanut shell powder as the raw material to leverage the fluorescent properties of CDs. Subsequently, P-CDs were combined with TiO2 to obtain a pale-yellow P-CDs/TiO2 composite. Next, the P-CDs/TiO2@CS composite material was prepared by acidifying CS. In an acidic environment, the amino (–NH2) groups in the CS polymer undergo protonation to form –NH3
                        +, causing the CS polymer chains to expand and disperse due to electrostatic repulsion, which facilitates the attachment of P-CDs/TiO2 particles [23]. During this process, the P-CDs/TiO2 particles coordinate with the abundant active –NH2 and hydroxyl (–OH) groups in the CS molecular chains, leading to interchain cross-linking [27]. The entire CS network stabilizes the individual structural components within the gel through the synergistic effects of spontaneous entanglement, hydrogen bonding, and electrostatic forces, resulting in the formation of a self-supporting P-CDs/TiO2@CS composite material [28]. The optical properties of P-CDs were investigated under different lighting conditions (Fig. S2). Under ambient light, the P-CDs appeared colorless when illuminated with UV light at wavelengths of 312 and 365 nm. The P-CDs displayed strong blue fluorescence, having a maximum excitation wavelength (ex) of 385 nm and a peak emission wavelength (em) of 465 nm. The morphology of P-CDs, TiO2, and P-CDs/TiO2 was observed using TEM (Fig. 1
                        ). In Fig. 1a, spherical CDs are visible, while Fig. 1b shows a lattice spacing of 0.27 nm for P-CDs. A measurement was made of the particle size distribution of about 100P-CDs, and revealed a size range of 3.16–10.55 nm with an average diameter of 6.55 nm (Fig. 1c). In Fig. 1d, sheet-like TiO2 is observed, with a lattice spacing of 0.35 nm (Fig. 1e) corresponding to the (101) crystal plane [29]. The TEM image of P-CDs/TiO2 is shown in Fig. 1f, and the lattice structure is displayed in Fig. 1g, where the overlapping lattices of P-CDs (0.27 nm) and TiO2 (0.35 nm) within the same region indicate close interfacial contact between the P-CDs and TiO2 nanoparticles, confirming the successful formation of the P-CDs/TiO2 composite.
